snippet.textDisplay: What a wasted opportunity. Does the unveiling of the PS5 belong at the CES? No, not really. But in the face of Microsoft's decision to at least show off the appearance of the Series X, and a potential sampling of it's power, at the game awards it would have been a smart move. Instead we get the laziest design effort ever seen since the DualShock 2 became the DualShock 3. The 5 is literally the "P" flipped upside down with a line added to it. Whomever got paid for that three second Photoshop job made too much.

snippet.textDisplay:
Once again, Sony is playing the game smarter than Microsoft. Now let’s say the rumors of Sony having a weaker CPU is true, it necessarily does not make it the weaker system seeing how games rely on the GPU more, thus having a good CPU prevents bottlenecking and so on.

Let’s take a trip down memory lane. When 3rd party games first released on current gen, they were certainly better than the prior gen, but weren’t showing the full potential of the current gen. It also wasn’t until the middle of the current gen when we did start to see the home hitting titles like (insert your Witcher 3 like title here). Not to mention, both Microsoft and Sony gave their current systems a boost to maintain the current market needs for overall better gaming.

Essentially what I’m saying is; Sony does not need to be the more powerful system, because like the series X, were not even going to see the full potential of the system out the gate. Microsoft tends to put more power into their systems, yet, there’s not much to show for (in the beginning). By that point the marketing approach then turns into 1st party titles and community. If the PS5 cost less than the XBSX, more people may stick with PlayStation because of its success today. How many people do you know with an 8K tv? When Sony releases a new console, typically the popular tv models tend to drop in price, this being a 4K TV today. I’m not trying to be biased, but I do see the flaws which Microsoft has made in the many years to put them behind even with the better system hardware. Even their egregious monetization efforts back on the 360 era, withheld many from owning a system. Xbox began charging people to play online before Sony, yet you have to wonder where the investment went due to lack of games this generation.

I could go on, but I must digress. This is a beefy subject, and honestly I’m setting this as a playing ground for debate/ discussion.
